\cf4 \cb3 Actually, I realize there's a subtlety with Sinatra's 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 enable :logging
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 .\cb1 \
\cb3 In Sinatra modular apps, 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 enable :logging
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  adds the Rack::Logger middleware and makes the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 logger
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  method available in route handlers, which should work perfectly for accessing the logger in my helpers and routes. I just need to make sure the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 log_error
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  helper is accessible across all route modules, and it will be since I'm defining it in the main api.rb file.\cb1 \
\cb3 Let me now write the changes to api.rb:\cb1 \
\cb3 Implementing the logging setup...\cb1 \
\cb3 For the payment service, I'll switch to using 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 warn
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  for stderr logging and clean up the error messages by removing the extra newline and exception details from the Result message.\cb1 \
\cb3 Across all 24 route files, I need to add the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 log_error
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  calls and strip out the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 \\n#\{e\}
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  fragments from error messages.\cb1 \
\cb3 Now looking at the N+1 query problems in memberAction.rb. The 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 get_member_actions
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  method is running multiple queries for each action\'97fetching the member, auth user, and related records separately instead of batching them. I need to preload these associations to collapse this into a single query with eager loading.\cb1 \
\cb3 Building out the fix by collecting all the IDs upfront and preloading members, auth users, and their associated members in bulk, then using a hash lookup instead of individual database calls for each action.\cb1 \
\cb3 Now I need to understand the schema for the events table to write the query correctly. The join table is 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 members_events
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  with 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 member_id
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  and 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 event_id
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 , and events have a timestamp field. I'm writing a query to find members who attended events in the last 90 days by joining the tables and filtering on the date. I'm building a query that joins the members_events table with events to filter by the 90-day window, selecting distinct member IDs who attended events in that timeframe. I need to verify the date comparison logic works correctly with the timestamp column. I'm second-guessing the exact boundary condition here\'97using 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 ts > (Date.today - 90)
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  at midnight is slightly more inclusive than the strict date comparison, but it's close enough for practical purposes, so I'll stick with that approach.\cb1 \
\cb3 Now I need to implement the full solution across multiple files. I'll start with api.rb to add logging support, then update the payment service to use proper warning logs, then systematically go through each route file to add error logging and clean up the exception messages. For the data-heavy routes like member actions and renewals, I'll preload the necessary associations to avoid N+1 queries. The rescue blocks across different files have varying indentation levels, so I'll need to be careful about consistency when adding the logging calls.\cb1 \
\cb3 Before I start writing though, I should verify that Sinatra's logging setup works correctly in modular apps with registered modules\'97specifically whether the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 logger
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  method is available in the context where I need it.\cb1 \
\cb3 In a Sinatra modular app, 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 enable :logging
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  adds the Rack::Logger middleware, and the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 logger
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  method comes from Sinatra::Helpers, which gets evaluated in the context of the Sinatra::Base instance. Since route blocks in registered modules run in that same context, they'll have access to the logger. So I can safely define a 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 log_error
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  helper in the API class and use it across all the route files.\cb1 \
\cb3 Now I need to decide on the exact replacements\'97whether to keep user-facing error messages meaningful or make them generic\'97then write out all the edits efficiently.\cb1 \
\cb3 Refactoring the N+1 query in 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 get_member_actions
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 ... Preloading all needed data in bulk, then fetching the associated members for those auth users. Now I'm querying which actions have logs attached and identifying members who attended meetings within the last 90 days.\cb1 \
\cb3 Building the actions array... I'm extracting the member and auth user IDs from the renewal records, then loading those members and their associated auth users into hashes for quick lookup during the renewal event processing.\cb1 \
\cb3 Now I'm building the renewal event types lookup and iterating through each renewal record to construct the output array, pulling together the member details, the user who recorded it, and the event type information.\cb1 \
\cb3 Then I'm querying the database for member dues payments and if there are any, I'm extracting the unique member and auth user IDs, fetching those records into lookup hashes, and preparing to gather the associated member data for the payment records.\cb1 \
\cb3 Now I'm iterating through each payment to enrich it with member details like name and callsign, plus the callsign of whoever recorded the payment, and tagging each one as a dues payment event.\cb1 \
\cb3 I'm noticing there's potential overlap between the two member preloads since the sets of IDs might intersect, but keeping them separate for now is simpler and still avoids the N+1 problem. For the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 admin_routes.rb
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  file, I need to tackle similar N+1 issues in the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 renewal_find_result
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  helper where members are being looked up repeatedly in loops.\cb1 \
\cb3 Setting up preloads...\cb1 \
\cb3 For each payment in range, I'm checking if there's a later dues payment for that member\'97if so, skip them. Otherwise, I'm collecting their member details and payment date into a renewal list. Then I'm filtering out members who have renewal halted or already received two renewal contacts.\cb1 \
\cb3 The key thing I'm verifying: 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 payments_by_mbr
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  only contains dues payments (type 5), so when I check for later payments, I'm already working with the right subset. The original code loads all payments for a member and filters to dues within the loop, but my approach of preloading only dues payments is more efficient and produces the same result.\cb1 \
\cb3 Now I'm ready to implement the changes across multiple files: updating the API logging setup, fixing error handling in the payment service, adding rescue blocks to the route files, and preloading the necessary payment data in the member actions and renewal routes. Writing rescue blocks... Adding error logging across the remaining route files... I'm seeing more error handling patterns across the renewal routes file\'97there are standalone date parsing blocks that wrap 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 Date.strptime
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  calls with rescue handlers that log errors and redirect, plus additional rescue blocks scattered throughout the file following the same structure as the other routes. I need to document all these parallel edits systematically.\cb1 \
\cb3 Let me organize this into phases: first I'll handle the simpler string interpolation removals and logging additions across the API and payment service files, then tackle all the rescue block standardizations across the seven route files in parallel, followed by the N+1 query fixes in the three files that need them, and finally run the test suite.\cb1 \
\cb3 For the event_routes.rb case specifically, I need to clean up that rescue block by removing the commented-out backtrace puts since log_error will handle that automatically, then verify that Sinatra's logger is properly configured through the enable :logging directive.\cb1 \
