\cf4 \cb3 The rest of the member manager options\'97database queries, referral management, unit and payment tracking, logging, attendance, and events\'97will go into this collapsible section to reduce visual clutter while keeping everything accessible. So "Members Table" should move to the hidden section since the user only specified keeping "List Members" and "Members & ARRL" visible in that card. The main card below will contain the renewal and survey items, and everything else goes into a collapsible "More..." section. I'm realizing the standard approach here would be a collapsible "More options" button that toggles visibility of the hidden section using Tailwind's 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 hidden
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  class. The user specifically asked for a hidden div with a toggle button, so that's the right direction. Let me map out the layout more carefully based on what they want visible versus hidden. Writing the HTML layout... Building the navigation menu... Building navigation links... I'm realizing there's an issue with how I'm handling the visibility toggle\'97using 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 classList.toggle('hidden')
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  will remove the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 display: none
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  property, but the element needs to display as 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 flex
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  with wrapping when shown, not just as a block, so I need to adjust the approach to properly manage both the hidden state and the flex layout. but then the element falls back to its default display. If I have 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 flex
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  in the class list, it would apply when 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 hidden
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  is removed... wait no, because 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 hidden
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  in Tailwind is 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 display: none !important
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 , which overrides everything. When 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 hidden
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  is removed, the remaining classes take effect. So if the element has 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 flex flex-wrap ...
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  in its class list along with 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 hidden
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 , when you remove 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 hidden
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 , the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 flex
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  class takes effect.\cb1 \
\cb3 So the correct approach is to keep both 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 hidden
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  and 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 flex
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  in the class list. When 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 hidden
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  is present, 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 display: none !important
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  applies. When 
