\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 PER_PAGE
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  is a constant defined inside the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 API
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  class, but the route modules are defined separately in 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 self.registered(app)
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  methods and they define routes via 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 app.get
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 , 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 app.post
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 , etc. The route blocks run in the context of the Sinatra app instance (which IS the API class), but 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 PER_PAGE
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  is a constant defined inside the class body.\cb1 \
\cb3 In Ruby, constants defined inside a class are accessible from within that class. But when route blocks (procs) are evaluated in the Sinatra app instance context, constants defined in outer contexts may not be directly accessible by name.\cb1 \
\cb3 Actually, I'm realizing the real issue: constants in Ruby are resolved at lexical scope where they're defined, not where they're evaluated. So when a route block in 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 log_routes.rb
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  references 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 PER_PAGE
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 , it's looking for that constant in the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 MemberTracker::LogRoutes
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  module scope, not in 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 MemberTracker::API
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  where it's actually defined. The route blocks need to explicitly reference 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 MemberTracker::API::PER_PAGE
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  to access it. I need to think through Ruby's constant lookup chain more carefully. When 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 PER_PAGE
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  is referenced inside the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 LogRoutes
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  module's registered block, Ruby will search up through the lexical scopes\'97first checking 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 LogRoutes
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 , then 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 MemberTracker
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 , then 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 Object
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 \'97so defining it at the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 MemberTracker
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  module level should make it accessible throughout the module hierarchy. 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 PER_PAGE
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  in 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 MemberTracker
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  at the module level makes it accessible to both the route blocks (which look up constants through 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 MemberTracker::LogRoutes
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 's nesting) and the helper methods in the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 API
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  class (which look up through 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 API
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 's nesting that includes 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 MemberTracker
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 ). So the solution is to define the constant at the module level rather than inside the class. Moving 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 PER_PAGE
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  to the module level so both the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 LogRoutes
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  module and the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 API
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  class can access it through the same constant lookup chain.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa51\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 PER_PAGE
\f1\fs26 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2  is defined inside the 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 API
\f1\fs26 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2  class but the route modules' blocks resolve constants via their own lexical scope (
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 MemberTracker::LogRoutes
\f1\fs26 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2  etc.) \'97 it's not visible there. Fix: move it to the 
