\cf4 \cb3 But I should present this as a recommendation and let the user decide whether to proceed.\cb1 \
\cb3 Looking at the specifics, the payments N+1 is particularly bad\'97each payment row triggers queries for the member, auth user, auth user's member, payment type, method, and log, which adds up to roughly 125-150 queries for a single page of 25 payments. The log N+1 follows a similar pattern with member and nested auth user associations.\cb1 \
\cb3 The event list N+1 is more straightforward\'97it's hitting the auth user's member and event type for each row, which amounts to around 100 extra queries per page. The key insight is that with pagination in place, these are now bounded to the page size rather than potentially thousands of rows, so the practical impact is significantly reduced even though the queries are still wasteful.\cb1 \
\cb3 Given that we've just touched both the event list and payments code, I'd prioritize fixing those two while noting that the logs have similar issues but are less critical. This feels like a "nice to have" improvement rather than something urgent, especially since the small club's internal tool will still perform acceptably on Heroku's free tier.\cb1 \
