\f0\b\fs26 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 The honest assessment:
\f1\b0  Pagination substantially changed the calculus. Before, an unbounded member list could mean thousands of queries. Now these are all capped at 25 rows, so the worst case is ~150 queries per page load \'97 and for PostgreSQL on a small dataset, that still renders in under 100ms.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 My recommendation:
\f1\b0  Don't fix them now. Here's why:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls24\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The three we fixed earlier were genuinely unbounded loops. These are now pagination-bounded.\cb1 \
\ls24\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Payments and logs are the most complex to preload correctly (multiple associations per row, conditional log fetch). The code change is meaningful effort for a small club's internal tool.\cb1 \
\ls24\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The event list N+1 is in the view itself (
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 e_list.erb
\f1\fs26 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 ) \'97 fixing it properly requires moving that logic into the route, which is a more structural change.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa51\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 If you wanted to address one, the 
\f0\b payments route
\f1\b0  is the best candidate because it has the most queries per row (6) and is probably the most-visited data-heavy page. The log routes are similar. The event list view is worth fixing if you're in there for another reason.\cb1 \
\cb3 The bigger wins remaining on the list from the audit are CSRF protection and pagination for the member list \'97 those have broader impact than these bounded N+1s.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb9 Ok, lets skip these N+1 issues just raised. I use the browser 'find' feature to add members to an event so displaying them all helps with this. Unless there is a more standard way of selecting from hundreds of potential individuals, let's keep that system for events. Maybe it would be better to have a search field on the members list and paginate that as well as with the home page. Lets implement that unless you can suggest a better way to view and find individual members.\cb1 \
\
