\cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 The user confirmed it was a caching issue! They turned off caching in Firefox DevTools Network tab and it worked. Now they're asking whether this will be an issue for other users.\cb1 \
\cb3 The answer is: this is a one-time problem that happened because they've been iterating on script.js during development while the browser cached the old version.\cb1 \
\cb3 For regular users:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa51\partightenfactor0
\ls57\ilvl0\cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 They've never loaded the old version of script.js, so they have nothing cached\cb1 \
\ls57\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Even if they had cached it, browsers respect Cache-Control headers. If Heroku/Puma serves script.js without aggressive caching headers (or with short TTL), users won't have stale caches\cb1 \
\ls57\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 The event_create form is only used by 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 mbr_mgr
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  users, so the blast radius is small\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa51\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb3 But there's a real concern with existing production users\'97anyone who's already visited the app will have the old script.js cached, and when I deploy the new HTML form, they'll get the updated template but stale validation logic, causing the same failure. The solution is cache busting by appending a version parameter to the script URL so browsers treat it as a new resource.\cb1 \
\cb3 Heroku might handle this automatically with proper Cache-Control headers, but Sinatra's default static file serving doesn't add aggressive caching directives, so browsers fall back to their own heuristics. The safest approach is adding 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 ?v=2
\f1\fs26 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4  to the script.js reference\'97this guarantees a fresh fetch whenever I increment the version, and I should explain this pattern for future updates.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa51\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Yes, this is a real risk for existing production users. Your browser had cached the old 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 script.js
\f1\fs26 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 , and when you deployed new HTML (with the hidden field instead of radio buttons) but the browser served the old JS (still checking radio buttons), it broke. New users who've never visited the app won't have that problem \'97 but any existing user who has opened the app recently will have the old file cached and hit the same failure when you deploy.\cb1 \
\cb3 The fix is a version query string on the script tag. Browsers treat 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 /js/script.js?v=2
\f1\fs26 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2  as a different URL from 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 /js/script.js
\f1\fs26 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 , so they fetch it fresh. You just need to increment the version number whenever you change 
\f2\fs23\fsmilli11700 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 script.js
\f1\fs26 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 .\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

